data.value: The first inhabitants of the Japanese islands, starting from 8,000 years ago, were thought to have come from North Asia and lived in the Upper Chipped (or at least Ortatas) period. Towards 538, the arrival of Buddhism from Korea to the islands is generally regarded as the beginning of Japan's history. Japan was an empire ruled by a feudal administration for centuries. Due to its location at the easternmost part of Asia and its being an island state, it was ruled by a closed state structure for centuries. On March 10, 1854, Commodore Matthew C. Perry and the US Navy's Black Ships forced the Japanese to open up to the outside world with the Kanagawa Convention. Similar treaties with Western countries in the following period brought economic and political crises. Japan, who suffered heavy losses from World War II, quickly gathered itself. According to the Constitution of Japan, the emperor is ğin the symbol of the unity of the state and of the people in and plays a ceremonial role without the right to sovereignty. Sovereignty belongs to the Japanese people.
